Social Research and Technology Innovation Laboratory (STRI) Data Analytics¶

Champaign Municipality City Works Complaints Data

This notebook provides data visualizations from Champaign County in Illinois for public city work complaints. The data were provided by the city of of Champaign and provide information on the description of the complaint, time of complaint, time complaint was closed, and geo-spatial data. In this notebook, the data are cleaned, processed, and visualized to provide insight on public work issues in the local Champaign area. The findings are intended to assist the local community leaders in making decisions on how to improve the community environment. [https://srtilab.techservices.illinois.edu/about/]

*** THE DATA PROVIDED HERE ARE UPDATED WITH 2018 DATA & MONTH BREAKDOWNS.

# Create transformation to transform numerals into month names
def Month (row):
    if row['month_int'] == 1:
        return 'January'
    if row['month_int'] == 2: 
        return 'February'
    if row['month_int'] == 3:
        return 'March'
    if row['month_int'] == 4:
        return 'April' 
    if row['month_int'] == 5:
        return 'May'
    if row['month_int'] == 6:
        return 'June'
    if row ['month_int'] == 7:
        return 'July'
    if row['month_int'] == 8:
        return 'August'
    if row['month_int'] == 9:
        return 'September'
    if row['month_int'] == 10:
        return 'October'
    if row['month_int'] == 11:
        return 'November'
    if row['month_int'] == 12:
        return 'December'

Create Function Returning Graph of Top Issues by Month when Month Argument is Passed¶

In this section, I write a function such that when a string is passed into the function "month_function(month)", the function will return a graph for the top 10 cityworks complaints for that month. This function works by first retriveving the correct month column from the dataframe, grouping by this month name, finding the top complaints under the "description" column, and then returning am ax figure instance. Please send in the abbreviated month name with qoute marks where it says 'TYPE MONTH', in the third column below. You can send in 'Nov', 'Dec', 'Jan', and so forth.

In [18]:
# Define the month function below. Please feel free to move to the next cell for visualizations. 
month_x = ''
def month_function(month):
    month_x = cityWorks[cityWorks['Month']== month]
    
    month_x['Description Count'] = month_x.groupby('DESCRIPTION')['DESCRIPTION'].transform('count')
    sorted_month = month_x.sort_values('Description Count',  ascending=False)
    top_month = sorted_month.drop_duplicates(subset=['DESCRIPTION']).head(15)

    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 7))
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    ax.set_xlabel("Year", size=13)
    ax.set_ylabel("Complaint Count", size=13)
    suptitle("Top 15 Complaints in" + " " + month, size=20)
    ax = sns.barplot(x="Description Count",y='DESCRIPTION', data=top_month, palette='muted', hue='Month')
        
    fig = ax.get_figure()

In [26]:
def year_function(year):
    
    year_x = cityWorks[cityWorks['Year']== year]
    year_x['Description Count'] = year_x.groupby('DESCRIPTION')['DESCRIPTION'].transform('count')
    sorted_year = year_x.sort_values('Description Count',  ascending=False)
    sort5_year = sorted_year.drop_duplicates(subset=['DESCRIPTION']).head(15)

    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 7))
    sns.set(style="whitegrid")
    ax.set_xlabel("Year", size=13)
    ax.set_ylabel("Complaint Count", size=13)
    suptitle("Top 15 Complaints {0}".format(year), size=20)
    ax = sns.barplot(x="Description Count",y='DESCRIPTION', data=sort5_year, palette='muted', hue='Year')

    fig = ax.get_figure()

Complaints by Addresses¶

# Define a new row for top occuring issues
def top_issues (row):
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Pothole repair' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Sewer backup' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Pick up dead animal(s)' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Pick up miscellaneous debris' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Tree inspection' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Tree branch on ROW needs to picked up' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Request to repair a burnt out streetlight lamp' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Misc. request/problem involving City facilities' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Tree pruning' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Snow & Ice mailbox repair' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Clean inlet' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Tree removal' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Signal not cycling properly' :
        return 1
    if row['DESCRIPTION'] == 'Plow request' :
        return 1     
    else: 
        return np.nan
In [40]:
# create new column with the above data, create new dataframe and remove all nan
cityWorks_int['top_issues'] = cityWorks_int.apply(lambda row: top_issues(row),axis=1)

cityWorks_intMap = cityWorks_int.dropna()
